    "summary": "Agrees on custom types vs validator discussion",
    "content": "Kent, thank you for the thorough mapping. You have captured everything accurately.\n\nOn the `validator` vs custom types question -- I suspect you are right that Scott will prefer the custom types approach, and I am inclined to agree with him. A newtype like `Email(String)` that validates at construction time and cannot exist in an invalid state is more idiomatic Rust than runtime validation with the `validator` crate. It aligns with \"make illegal states unrepresentable\" and eliminates an entire class of bugs. We validate once at the parsing boundary (HTTP handler), and from that point forward the type system guarantees correctness.\n\nThe `validator` crate is useful when you have many complex validation rules on a single struct (like a registration form with 10 fields), but for domain types, parsing into newtypes is the stronger pattern. We can use both -- `validator` for form-level validation at the HTTP boundary, custom types for domain-level invariants. But I am happy to let the mob decide when we encounter the first concrete case.\n\nI will wait for the consolidated revision. Looking forward to reviewing it."
  }
